# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cutoff-steam-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] A **beam engine** is a type of steam engine where a pivoted overhead beam is used to apply the force from a vertical piston to a vertical connecting rod.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This configuration, with the engine directly driving a pump, was first used by Thomas Newcomen around 1705 to remove water from mines in Cornwall.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The efficiency of the engines was improved by engineers including James Watt, who added a separate condenser; Jonathan Hornblower and Arthur Woolf, who compounded the cylinders; and William McNaught, who devised a method of compounding an existing engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Beam engines were first used to pump water out of mines or into canals but could be used to pump water to supplement the flow for a waterwheel powering a mill.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The **rotative beam engine** is a later design of beam engine where the connecting rod drives a flywheel by means of a crank (or, historically, by means of a sun and planet gear).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] These beam engines could be used to directly power the line-shafting in a mill.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] They also could be used to power steam ships.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The first beam engines were water-powered and used to pump water from mines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] A preserved example may be seen at the Straitsteps Lead Mine in Wanlockhead in Scotland.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Beam engines were extensively used to power pumps on the English canal system when it was expanded by means of locks early in the Industrial Revolution, and also to drain water from mines in the same period, and as winding engines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The first steam-related beam engine was developed by Thomas Newcomen.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This was not, strictly speaking, steam powered, as the steam introduced below the piston was condensed to create a partial vacuum thus allowing atmospheric pressure to push down the piston.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] It was therefore called an Atmospheric Engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The Newcomen atmospheric engine was adopted by many mines in Cornwall and elsewhere, but it was relatively inefficient and consumed a large quantity of fuel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The engine was improved by John Smeaton but James Watt resolved the main inefficiencies of the Newcomen engine in his Watt steam engine by the addition of a separate condenser, thus allowing the cylinder to remain hot.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Technically this was still an atmospheric engine until (under subsequent patents) he enclosed the upper part of the cylinder, introducing steam to also push the piston down.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This made it a true steam engine and arguably confirms him as the inventor of the steam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] He also patented the centrifugal governor and the parallel motion. the latter allowed the replacement of chains round an arch head and thus allowed its use as a rotative engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] His patents remained in place until the start of the 19th Century and some say that this held back development.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] However, in reality development had been ongoing by others and at the end of the patent period there was an explosion of new ideas and improvements.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Watt's beam engines were used commercially in much larger numbers and many continued to run for 100 years or more.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Watt held patents on key aspects of his engine's design, but his rotative engine was equally restricted by James Pickard's patent of the simple crank.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The beam engine went on to be considerably improved and enlarged in the tin- and copper-rich areas of south west England, which enabled the draining of the deep mines that existed there.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Consequently, the Cornish beam engines became world-famous, as they remain among the most massive beam engines ever constructed.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Because of the number of patents on various parts of the engines and the consequences of patent infringements, examples exist of Beam Engines with no makers name on any of the parts (Hollycombe Steam Collection).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] In a rotative beam engine, the piston is mounted vertically, and the piston rod drives the beam as before.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] A connecting rod from the other end of the beam, rather than driving a pump rod, now drives a flywheel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Early Watt engines used Watt's patent sun and planet gear, rather than a simple crank, as use of the latter was protected by a patent owned by James Pickard.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Once the patent had expired, the simple crank was employed universally.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Once rotary motion had been achieved a drive belt could be attached beside the flywheel.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This transmitted the power to other drive shafts and from these other belts could then be attached to power a variety of static machinery e.g. threshing, grinding or milling machines.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The first steam-powered ships used variants of the rotative beam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] These marine steam engines – known as side-lever, grasshopper, crosshead, or 'walking beam', among others – all varied from the original land-based machines by locating the beam or beams in different positions to take up less room on board ship.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Compounding involves two or more cylinders; low-pressure steam from the first, high-pressure, cylinder is passed to the second cylinder where it expands further and provides more drive.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This is the compound effect; the waste steam from this can produce further work if it is then passed into a condenser in the normal way.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The first experiment with compounding was conducted by Jonathan Hornblower, who took out a patent in 1781.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] His first engine was installed at Tincroft Mine, Cornwall.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] It had two cylinders – one 21-inch (0.53 m) diameter with 6-foot (1.8 m) stroke and one 27-inch (0.69 m) diameter with 8-foot (2.4 m) stroke – placed alongside each other at one end of the beam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The early engines showed little performance gain: the steam pressure was too low, interconnecting pipes were of small diameter and the condenser ineffective.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] At this time the laws of thermodynamics were not adequately understood, particularly the concept of absolute zero.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Engineers such as Arthur Woolf were trying to tackle an engineering problem with an imperfect understanding of the physics.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] In particular, their valve gear was cutting-in at the wrong position in the stroke, not allowing for expansive working in the cylinder.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] Successful Woolf compound engines were produced in 1814, for the Wheal Abraham copper mine and the Wheal Vor tin mine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] William McNaught patented a compound beam engine in 1845.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] On a beam engine of the standard Boulton & Watt design he placed a high-pressure cylinder, on the opposite side of the beam to the existing single cylinder, where the water pump was normally fitted.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This had two important effects: it massively reduced the pressure on the beam, and the connecting steam pipe, being long, acted as an expansive receiver – the element missing in the Woolf design.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] This modification could be made retrospectively, and engines so modified were said to be "McNaughted".
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/beam-engine] The advantages of a compound engine were not significant at pressures under 60 pounds per square inch (410 kPa), but showed at over 100 psi (690 kPa).
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] In a steam engine, **cutoff** is the point in the piston stroke at which the inlet valve is closed.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] On a steam locomotive, the cutoff is controlled by the reversing gear.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] The point at which the inlet valve closes and stops the entry of steam into the cylinder from the boiler plays a crucial role in the control of a steam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Once the valve has closed, steam trapped in the cylinder expands adiabatically.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] A late cutoff delivers full steam pressure to move the piston through its entire stroke, for maximum start-up forces.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] But, since there will still be unexploited pressure in the cylinder at the end of the stroke, this is achieved at the expense of engine efficiency.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] In this situation the steam will still have considerable pressure remaining when it is exhausted resulting in the characteristic “chuff chuff” sound of a steam engine.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] An early cutoff has greater thermodynamic efficiency but results in a lower mean effective pressure so less average force on the piston and is used for running the engine at higher speeds.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Early cutoff is used to increase the efficiency of the engine by allowing the steam to expand for the rest of the power stroke, yielding more of its energy and conserving steam.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Late cutoff is used to provide maximum torque to the shaft at the expense of efficiency and is used to start the engine under load.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Cutoff is conventionally expressed as percentage of the power stroke of the piston; if the piston is at a quarter of its stroke at the cutoff point, the cutoff is stated as 25%.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Smaller stationary steam engines generally have a fixed cutoff point while, in large ones, the speed and power output is generally governed by altering the cutoff, frequently under governor control using an expansion valve or trip gear.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] In steam engines for transport, it is desirable to be able to alter the cutoff over a wide range.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] In steam locomotives, for starting and at low speed and heavy load, the cylinders need moderate steam supply (by throttling the steam supply pressure) throughout most of the piston stroke.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] The lower pressure is used to avoid "wheel spin" that frequently occurs when starting a train onto motion.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] After establishing train moderate speed, the cutoff is reduced, and higher boiler pressure is admitted into the cylinders, which results in much better engine efficiency.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] In a two-cylinder locomotive, for example, the maximum or 'full gear' cutoff is typically about 85%.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] At high speeds, the cutoff may be significantly reduced.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Steam engines used in boats and ships typically also use variable cutoff valve gear, while some operate with a fixed cutoff, with speed being controlled through the regulator.
[src:cutoff-steam-engine/cutoff-steam-engine] Providing variable cutoff is an important function of the valve gear.
